 England \u2013 taking UK total to 104 |work=Sky News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The government announces that all schools in the country will shut from the afternoon of Friday 20 March, except for those looking after the children of key workers and vulnerable children.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51952314 |title=Coronavirus: Schools to close until further notice from Friday |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> No exams will take place this academic year, [[Secretary of State for Education|Education Secretary]] [[Gavin Williamson]] confirms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-uk-schools-to-close-from-friday-11959769 |title=Coronavirus: UK schools to close from Friday until further notice |work=Sky News |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The 50th anniversary [[Glastonbury Festival]] is cancelled as a result of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/mar/18/uk-coronavirus-live-boris-johnson-pmqs-cbi-urges-government-pay-businesses-directly-saying-350bn-loangrant-package-not-enough |title=All schools to close from Friday; GCSE and A-level exams cancelled \u2013 UK coronavirus, as it happened |work=The Guardian |date=18 March 2020 |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The government announces emergency legislation to bring in a complete ban on new evictions for three months, as part of measures to help protect renters in social and private rented accommodation.\n*19 March \u2013 In an emergency move, the Bank of England cuts interest rates again, from 0.25% to just 0.1%. This is the lowest rate in the Bank's 325-year history.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51962982 |title=Coronavirus: UK interest rates slashed to lowest level ever |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=19 March 2020 |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*20 March\n**[[Northwick Park Hospital]] in [[London Borough of Harrow|Harrow]] declares a \"critical incident\" due to a surge in patients with coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/news/hospitals-critical-care-unit-overwhelmed-by-coronavirus-patients/7027189.article |title=Hospital's critical care unit overwhelmed by coronavirus patients |work=HSJ |publisher=HSJ|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Chancellor Rishi Sunak announces that the government will pay 80% of wages for employees not working, up to \u00a32,500 a month, as part of \"unprecedented\" measures to protect people's jobs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51982005 |title=Wages cover for businesses hit by virus outlined |publisher=BBC News|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Prime Minister Boris Johnson orders all cafes, pubs and restaurants to close from the evening of 20 March, except for take-away food, to tackle coronavirus. All the UK's nightclubs, theatres, cinemas, gyms and leisure centres are told to close \"as soon as they reasonably can\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51981653 |title=UK pubs and restaurants told to shut in virus fight |publisher=BBC News|date=20 March 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n*21 March \u2013 [[Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs|Environment Secretary]] [[George Eustice]] urges shoppers to stop [[panic buying]], as supermarkets around the UK struggle to keep up with demand.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51989721 |title=Coronavirus: Shoppers told to buy responsibly |publisher=BBC News|date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> [[Tesco]], [[Asda]], [[Aldi]], and [[Lidl]] are reported to have begun a recruitment drive for up to 30,000 new staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-51976075 |title=Supermarkets Tesco, Asda, Aldi and Lidl go on hiring spree |publisher=BBC News|date=21 March 2020 |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n*22 March\n**The [[Nursing and Midwifery Council]] announces that more than 5,600 former nurses have registered to offer their services in the fight against coronavirus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2020/mar/22/uk-coronavirus-live-police-could-enforce-london-lockdown-says-khan-seven-people-die-in-wales?page=with:block-5e776a4f8f08dcc95cc20fdd#block-5e776a4f8f08dcc95cc20fdd |title=UK coronavirus live: police could enforce London social distancing; seven people die in Wales |work=The Guardian|date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Boris Johnson warns that \"tougher measures\" may be introduced if people do not follow government advice on social distancing.<ref name=\"tougher measures\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-51998559 |title=Coronavirus: Follow virus advice or 'tougher measures' likely, says PM |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=22 March 2020 |accessdate=22 March 2020}}</ref> \n**The virus claims its youngest victim so far, with the death of an eighteen-year-old with underlying health problems.<ref name=\"tougher measures\"/>\n*23 March\n**The government announces emergency measures to safeguard the nation's [[Rail transport in the United Kingdom|rail network]], with season ticket holders given refunds if working from home, and [[Passenger rail franchising in Great Britain|rail franchise agreements]] nationalised for at least six months to prevent rail companies from collapsing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52002272 |title=Commuters to get refund on rail season tickets |publisher=BBC News|date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-rail-franchise-agreements-suspended-to-avoid-company-collapses-11962186 |title=Coronavirus: Rail franchise agreements suspended to avoid company collapses |publisher=Sky News|date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Pride in London]], the UK's largest LGBT [[Pride festival]], scheduled for 27 June, is the latest event to be postponed. It is one of a hundred pride events to be postponed or cancelled in the UK.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hunte |first=Ben |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52001388 |title=Coronavirus postpones London Pride |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=23 March 2020 |accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n**In a televised address, Boris Johnson announces a UK-wide lockdown with immediate effect, to contain the spread of the virus. People can leave their homes only for \"very limited purposes\" \u2013 shopping for basic necessities; for one form of exercise a day; for any medical need; and to travel to and from work when \"absolutely necessary\". A number of other restrictions are imposed, with police given powers to enforce the measures, including the use of fines.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/world-52000039 |title='You must stay at home' UK public told| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52012432 |title=Coronavirus: Strict new curbs on life in UK announced by PM| publisher=BBC | date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/23/boris-johnson-orders-uk-lockdown-to-be-enforced-by-police |title=Boris Johnson orders UK lockdown to be enforced by police| work=The Guardian| date=23 March 2020| accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n*24 March\n**The UK records its highest number of coronavirus deaths in one day, after a further 87 people die across the country, bringing the total to 422.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-calls-for-police-at-stations-after-packed-trains-defy-lockdown-11962837|title=Coronavirus: Biggest daily rise in UK deaths \u2013 up by 87 to 422\n| publisher=Sky News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**For the first time, all of the UK's [[List of mobile network operators of Europe#United Kingdom|mobile networks]] send out a government text alert, ordering people to stay at home. The message reads: \"''GOV.UK CORONAVIRUS ALERT. New rules in force now: you must stay at home. More info and exemptions at gov.uk/coronavirus Stay at home. Protect the NHS. Save lives.''\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-52017451|title=Coronavirus: Mobile networks send 'stay at home' text| publisher=BBC News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Secretary of State for Health|Health Secretary]] [[Matt Hancock]] announces the government will open a temporary hospital, the [[NHS Nightingale Hospital]] at the [[ExCeL London]], to add extra critical care capacity in response to coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-52018477|title=Coronavirus: ExCeL Centre planned as NHS field hospital| publisher=BBC News| date=24 March 2020| accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Scottish Parliament]] closes, with plans to reconvene on 1 April to discuss emergency legislation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-52018354 |title=FMQs cancelled as Holyrood chamber shuts for a week |work=BBC News |date=24 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*25 March\n**[[Prince Charles]] tests positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52033845|title=Coronavirus: Prince Charles tests positive but 'remains in good health'| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] shuts down for a month.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52032188|title=Coronavirus: Parliament shuts down for a month| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[British Transport Police]] deploys 500 officers to patrol the UK's rail network, in an effort to discourage non-essential journeys. New measures are also introduced on the [[London Underground]] to reduce passenger numbers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-52023580|title=Coronavirus: New Tube restrictions to stop non-essential journeys| publisher=BBC News| date=25 March 2020| accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n*26 March\n**The government announces that the [[Self-employment|self-employed]] will be paid 80% of profits, up to \u00a32,500 a month, to help them cope during the economic crisis triggered by COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52053914|title=Coronavirus: UK government unveils aid for self-employed| publisher=BBC News| date=26 March 2020| accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n**At 8pm, millions of people around the country take part in a \"[[Clap for our Carers|Clap for Carers]]\" tribute, applauding the NHS and other care workers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52058013|title=Clap for Carers: UK in 'emotional' tribute to NHS and care workers| publisher=BBC News| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n*27 March\n**Prime Minister Boris Johnson tests positive for COVID-19, and will self-isolate in [[10 Downing Street]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52060791|title=PM Boris Johnson tests positive for coronavirus| publisher=BBC News| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n**Health Secretary [[Matt Hancock]] tests positive for COVID-19 and reports that he is working from home and self-isolating.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/coronavirus-matt-hancock-boris-johnson-test-positive-covid-19-symptoms-a9430031.html|title=Coronavirus: Health secretary Matt Hancock tests positive| work=The Independent| date=27 March 2020| accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Leon Restaurants]] sets up the \"[[Feed NHS]]\" initiative to deliver 5,600 free meals a day to [[National Health Service|NHS]] [[intensive care medicine|critical care]] staff at London hospitals.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Butler|first=Sarah|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/27/leon-sets-up-initiative-to-deliver-free-hot-meals-to-nhs-staff-coronavirus|title=Leon sets up initiative to deliver free meals to NHS critical care staff|date=2020-03-27|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-29|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n*28 March \u2013 At 11pm, new regulations come into force in Northern Ireland giving authorities the power to force businesses to close, and impose fines on them if they refuse, as well as on people leaving their homes without a \"reasonable excuse\". The measures, introduced by the [[Northern Ireland Executive]], bring Northern Ireland into line with the rest of the UK.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52079959 |title=New NI Covid-19 regulations come into force |work=BBC News |date=28 March 2020 |via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-28/new-regulations-to-enforce-coronavirus-restrictions-agreed-by-stormont/ |title=Northern Ireland imposes fines up to \u00a35,000 for those breaching social distancing rules |website=ITV News}}</ref>\n*30 March \u2013 [[Foreign Secretary]] [[Dominic Raab]] announces an arrangement between the government and major UK airlines to fly home tens of thousands of British nationals who are stranded abroad by the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52099252|title=Rescue flights for stranded Britons|work=BBC News|date=30 March 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*31 March \u2013 A significant rise in [[anxiety]] and [[Depression (mood)|depression]] among the UK population is reported following the lockdown. The study, by researchers from the [[University of Sheffield]] and [[Ulster University]], finds that people reporting anxiety increased from 17% to 36%, while those reporting depression increased from 16% to 38%.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/31/rise-in-depression-and-anxiety-day-after-uk-lockdown-announced-study-coronavirus |title=Rise in depression and anxiety day after UK lockdown announced \u2013 study| work=The Guardian| date=31 March 2020| accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n*1 April\n**The [[contactless payment]] limit for in-store spending is raised from \u00a330 to \u00a345.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2020/mar/24/limit-for-contactless-spending-to-rise-to-45-at-beginning-of-april|title=Limit for contactless spending to rise to \u00a345 at beginning of April|work=The Guardian|date=24 March 2020|accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[National Assembly for Wales]] reconvenes using [[Zoom (software)|Zoom]] for a virtual emergency [[Senedd Cymru|Senedd]] meeting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.assembly.wales/en/newhome/pages/newsitem.aspx?itemid=2092|title=Plenary meetings continue, but Senedd buildings will stay closed until June|website=National Assembly for Wales|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n**Multinational pharmaceutical company [[Hoffmann-La Roche|Roche]] denies the existence of a deal to supply Wales with COVID-19 tests after First Minister [[Mark Drakeford]] and Health Minister [[Vaughan Gething]] blame the collapse of a deal for a shortage of testing kits.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/politics/mark-drakeford-roche-coronavirus-testing-18025301|title=Pharmaceutical giant Roche and Welsh Government at loggerheads over collapsed Covid-19 testing deal|date=1 April 2020|author=Will Hayward|website=WalesOnline|access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*3 April \u2013 [[NHS Nightingale Hospital London]], the first temporary hospital to treat coronavirus patients, opens at the [[ExCeL London|ExCel centre]] in East London, employing NHS staff and military personnel, with 500 beds and potential capacity for 4,000. It is the first of several such facilities planned across the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52150598|title=Coronavirus: Nightingale Hospital opens at London's ExCel centre|work=BBC News|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n*4 April \u2013 The results of the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]] and the [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election]] are announced, in which [[Keir Starmer]] is elected as the leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]], succeeding [[Jeremy Corbyn]], and [[Angela Rayner]] is elected as deputy leader of the party.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52164589|title=Keir Starmer elected as new Labour leader|work=BBC News|date=4 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n*5 April\n**[[Queen Elizabeth II]] makes a [[Addresses to the nation by Elizabeth II|rare broadcast to the UK]] and the wider Commonwealth, something she has done on only four previous occasions. In the address she thanks people for following the government's social distancing rules, pays tribute to key workers, and says the UK \"will succeed\" in its fight against coronavirus but may have \"more still to endure\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Caroline |last=Davies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/03/queen-to-address-nation-on-sunday-over-coronavirus-crisis |title=Queen to address nation on Sunday over coronavirus crisis |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=3 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52176222 |title=Coronavirus: Queen tells UK 'we will succeed' in fight |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n**Prime Minister Boris Johnson is admitted to hospital for tests after testing positive for coronavirus ten days earlier.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52177125 |title=Coronavirus: PM admitted to hospital over virus symptoms |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=5 April 2020 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n*6 April\n**The death toll from COVID-19 in the UK exceeds 5,000. The total number of reported cases is nearly 52,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2020/apr/06/uk-coronavirus-live-boris-johnson-spends-night-in-hospital?page=with:block-5e8b4c078f080bdb9f535404#block-5e8b4c078f080bdb9f535404|title=UK death toll rises to 5,373|publisher=The Guardian|date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n**Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is taken into [[intensive care unit|intensive care]] after being admitted to hospital for coronavirus the day before. It is announced that [[First Secretary of State]] [[Dominic Raab]] will deputise for him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52192604 |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson moved to intensive care |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=6 April 2020 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Orange Order|Orange Lodge of Ireland]] announces that the traditional [[Twelfth of July]] parades in Northern Ireland have been cancelled for 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-52184743 |title=Coronavirus: Twelfth of July parades cancelled due to outbreak|date= 6 April 2020 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n*8 April \u2013 The [[Resolution Foundation]], using figures from the [[British Chambers of Commerce]], reports that more than nine million workers are expected to be [[Furlough|furloughed]] under the government's job retention scheme, with an estimated cost to the taxpayer of between \u00a330 and 40bn.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52209790 |title=Coronavirus: More than 9 million expected to be furloughed |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=8 April 2020 |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n*9 April\n**Foreign Secretary [[Dominic Raab]] says the UK is \"starting to see the impact\" of the restrictions but that it is \"too early\" to lift them, and urges people to stay indoors over the Easter weekend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52235492|title=Raab urges UK public not to ruin lockdown progress|publisher=BBC News|date=9 April 2020}}</ref> \n**Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is moved out of intensive care, but remains in hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-52238276|title=PM out of intensive care but remains in hospital|publisher=BBC News|date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n*11 April\n**[[Queen Elizabeth II]] makes her first ever [[Easter]] [[Addresses to the nation by Elizabeth II|message to the nation]], in which she states \"coronavirus will not overcome us\" and that \"we need Easter as much as ever.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52255054 |title=Coronavirus: 'We need Easter as much as ever,' says the Queen |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=11 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The number of people in London hospitals for COVID-19 reaches its peak, according to week-on-week change data; elsewhere in the country, patient numbers continue to increase, although the rate of increase is slowing.<ref>{{Cite tweet|number=1250904238399598594|user=jburnmurdoch|title=Charts: London\u2019s hospitals now have fewer covid patients with each day|author=John Burn-Murdoch, [[Financial Times]]|date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n*12 April\n**Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] is discharged from hospital after being treated for coronavirus and will continue his recovery at [[Chequers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-52262012 |title=Coronavirus: Boris Johnson discharged from hospital |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The number of people who died in hospital with coronavirus in the UK passes 10,000, after a daily rise of 737.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52264145 |title=Coronavirus: 'Sombre day' as UK deaths hit 10,000 |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=12 April 2020 |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The temporary [[Dragon's Heart Hospital]] opens at Cardiff's [[Principality Stadium]] to admit its first patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/sport/rugby/rugby-news/giant-tents-built-inside-principality-18081445|title=Giant tents emerge over Principality Stadium pitch as pictures show first hospital wards at iconic venue|website=WalesOnline|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n*14 April\n**The [[Office of National Statistics]] indicates that coronavirus was linked to one in five deaths during the week ending 3 April. More than 16,000 deaths in the UK were recorded for that week, 6,000 higher than would be the average for that time of year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/health-52278825|title=One in five deaths now linked to coronavirus|first=Nick|last=Triggle|work=BBC News|date=14 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Several UK charities, including [[Age UK]] and the [[Alzheimer's Society]], express their concern that older people are being \"airbrushed\" out of official figures because they focus on hospital deaths and do not include those in care homes or a person's own home. Responding to these concerns, [[Therese Coffey]], the [[Secretary of State for Work and Pensions]], says that hospital figures are being used because \"it's accurate and quick\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52275823|title=Elderly being 'airbrushed' out of virus figures|work=BBC News|date=14 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Mobile operators report a further twenty attempted arson attacks on mobile phone masts over the previous weekend.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-52281315|title=Twenty suspected phone mast attacks over Easter|first=Leo|last=Kelion|work=BBC News|date=14 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*15 April\n**Health Secretary Matt Hancock announces new guidelines that will allow close family members to see dying relatives in order to say goodbye to them. Hancock also launches a new network to provide personal protective equipment to care home staff.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52299590|title=Coronavirus: Close family to be allowed to say goodbye to the dying - BBC News|work=BBC News|date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n**[[NHS England]] and the [[Care Quality Commission]] begin rolling out tests for care home staff and residents as it is reported the number of care home deaths are rising but that official figures, which rely on death certificates, are not reflecting the full extent of the problem. [[Helen Whately]], the Minister for Social Care, says that the government are aware the figures are being understated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/apr/15/coronavirus-death-toll-in-englands-care-homes-reaches-1400|title=Care homes in England say coronavirus death toll has risen to 1,400|first=Robert |last=Booth|date=15 April 2020|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n**[[Arlene Foster]], the [[First Minister of Northern Ireland]], extends the period of lockdown in Northern Ireland to 9 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-52298748|title=Three-week extension to NI coronavirus lockdown|first=Jayne|last=McCormack|date=15 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*16 April\n**A 99-year-old war veteran, [[Tom Moore (soldier)|Tom Moore]], raises over \u00a318 million for [[NHS Charities Together]] by walking 100 laps of his garden, with hundreds of thousands of people donating to his [[JustGiving]] page.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-52303859 |title=Coronavirus: Capt Tom Moore finishes NHS fundraiser as it tops \u00a313m |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n**Foreign Secretary [[Dominic Raab]] announces a three-week extension to the nationwide lockdown measures as the number of confirmed COVID-19 cases in the UK surpasses 100,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52313715 |title=Coronavirus: UK lockdown extended for 'at least three weeks' |work=BBC News |publisher=BBC |date=16 April 2020 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[NHS Nightingale Hospital Birmingham]], at the [[National Exhibition Centre]], is officially opened by [[William, Duke of Cambridge|Prince William]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-birmingham-52309494|title=Nightingale hospital 'example of pulling together'|date=16 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**The UK stages a fourth round of applause for NHS staff and key workers at 8pm.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-04-16/uk-clap-for-our-carers-nhs-coronavirus-lockdown/|title=UK unites for fourth week in nationwide Clap For Our Carers to thank NHS workers fighting coronavirus pandemic|website=ITV News}}</ref>\n*17 April \n**Matt Hancock confirms coronavirus tests will be rolled out to cover more public service staff such as police officers, firefighters and prison staff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52322447|title=Virus tests expanded to more public service staff|date=17 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> \n**Chancellor [[Rishi Sunak]] extends the subsidised wage scheme for furloughed workers for another month, to the end of June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-52323918|title=Government extends furlough scheme to pay staff|date=17 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n*18 April \u2013 \n**[[Imran Ahmad-Khan]], the MP for [[Wakefield (UK Parliament constituency)|Wakefield]], secures a shipment of of 110,000 reusable face masks through his connections with charity [[Solidarit\u00e9s international]] and the [[Government of Vietnam|Vietnamese Government]] for [[The Mid Yorkshire Hospitals NHS Trust|Mid Yorkshire Hospitals NHS Trust]] to help tackle the shortage of PPE.<ref name=ImranAhmadkhan-response>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/health/coronavirus/wakefield-mp-arranges-delivery-110000-reusable-face-masks-vietnam-nhs-2539775 |title=Wakefield MP arranges delivery of 110,000 reusable face masks from Vietnam for NHS|work=[[The Yorkshire Post]]|last= Scott|first=Geraldine| date=18 April 2020 |accessdate=18 April 2020 }}</ref>\n**Unions representing doctors and nurses express their concern at a change in government guidelines advising medics to reuse gowns or wear other kit if stocks run low.<ref name=\"BBC gowns\"/>\n**Speaking at the Downing Street daily briefing, [[Robert Jenrick]], the [[Secretary of State for Local Government]] says a further 400,000 gowns will be arriving from Turkey the following day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/uk-news/400000-more-gowns-nhs-arriving-18112744|title=400,000 more gowns for NHS arriving from Turkey tomorrow|first=Neil|last=Shaw|date=18 April 2020|website=walesonline}}</ref> \n**The number of recorded deaths rises by 888 to 15,464.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52335561|title=Concern over protective kit guidance change|date=18 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**[[Care England]], the UK's largest care homes representative body, estimates that as many as 7,500 care home residents may have died because of coronavirus, compared to the official figure of 1,400 released a few days earlier.<ref name=\"BBC gowns\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/18/uk-care-home-covid-19-deaths-may-be-five-times-government-estimate|title=UK care home Covid-19 deaths 'may be five times government estimate'|first=Molly|last=Blackall|date=18 April 2020|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n**Jenrick announces a further \u00a31.6bn of support for local authorities, on top of \u00a31.6bn that was given to them at the beginning of the outbreak.<ref name=\"18 April Briefing\"/>\n**Jenrick says that the virus appears to be having a \"disproportionate impact\" on the [[Black, Asian and minority ethnic]] (BAME) communities, while [[Stephen Powis]] says he has asked [[Public Health England]] to investigate what may be accounting for the increased risk within these groups.<ref name=\"18 April Briefing\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52339266|title=English councils to get extra \u00a31.6bn virus support|date=18 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n**Jenrick says that parks and cemeteries must remain open during the lockdown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-52339266|title=Parks and cemeteries must stay open, says minister|date=18 April 2020|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Portal bar|United Kingdom|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Timeline of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:British history timelines|Coronavirus]]\n", "name_user": "Pigsonthewing", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eApril:update)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_the_2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_the_United_Kingdom"}
{"title_page": "Howie Hawkins", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Howie Hawkins\n|image       = Hawkins 2010.jpg\n|birth_name = Howard Gresham Hawkins\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1952|12|8}}\n|birth_place = [[San Francisco]], [[California]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Green Party of the United States|Green]]\n|otherparty  = [[Socialist Party USA|Socialist]] (affiliated)<ref name=\"syracuse soc\">Mariani, John. {{cite web |title=Socialists back Howie Hawkins' Green bid for governor |url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2010/06/socialists_back_howie_hawkins.html |accessdate=June 15, 2010 |date=June 14, 2010}} ''The Syracuse Post Standard'', Monday June 14, 2010</ref>\n|education   = [[Dartmouth College]]\n|allegiance  = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch      = {{flag|United States Marine Corps}}\n}}{{Howie Hawkins series}}\n'''Howard Gresham Hawkins''' (born December 8, 1952) is an American trade unionist and [[political activism|activist]] from [[New York (state)|New York]]. A co-founder of the [[Green Party of the United States]], Hawkins is [[Howie Hawkins 2020 presidential campaign|seeking the party's nomination for President in 2020]]. His primary campaign issues include enacting an [[eco-socialism|eco-socialist]] [[Green New Deal]], which he first proposed in 2010, and building a viable, independent working-class political and social movement in opposition to the Democratic and Republican parties and capitalism in general.<ref name=\"IndependentPolitics2006\">{{cite book |last1=Hawkins |first1=Howie |title=Independent politics : the Green Party strategy debate |date=April 11, 2006 |publisher=Haymarket Books |isbn=9781931859301 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHawkins has played leading roles in [[Veterans for Peace|anti-war]],<ref name=\"VetsForPeace2016\">{{cite news |title=U.S. Vets Lead Civil Disobedience Action at Crestwood to Protest Seneca Lake Gas Storage |url=https://www.veteransforpeace.org/who-we-are/member-highlights/2016/01/27/us-vets-lead-civil-disobedience-action-crestwood-protest-sen |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=www.veteransforpeace.org |date=27 January 2016 |language=en}}</ref> [[Clamshell Alliance|anti-nuclear]],<ref name=\"NYT2018\">{{cite news |last1=McKinley |first1=Jesse |title=0-for-23: An Undeterred Green Party Candidate on His Long Losing Streak |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/19/nyregion/howie-hawkins-green-party-governor.html |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=19 October 2018}}</ref> and pro-worker movements since the 1960s. Hawkins is a retired [[International Brotherhood of Teamsters|teamster]] and construction worker; from 2001 until his retirement in 2017, Hawkins worked the night shift unloading trucks for [[United Parcel Service|UPS]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Chris |title=Syracuse\u2019s Howie Hawkins mulls a run for president |url=https://www.syracuse.com/politics/2019/04/syracuses-howie-hawkins-mulls-a-run-for-president-with-green-party.html |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=syracuse |date=3 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"EugeneWeekly\">{{cite news |title=It Ain\u2019t Easy Being Green |url=https://www.eugeneweekly.com/2020/01/09/it-aint-easy-being-green/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Eugene Weekly |date=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nHawkins has run for office on several occasions, all unsuccessfully. He was [[Green Party of New York|New York's Green Party]] candidate for the [[2006 New York United States Senate election|U.S. Senate]] in 2006. In 2010, Hawkins ran as the Green Party's candidate for [[2010 New York gubernatorial election|Governor of New York]], which restored ballot status for the party when it received more than the necessary 50,000 votes. In 2014, Hawkins ran again for the same office and received five percent of the vote. Hawkins ran a third time for Governor of New York in 2018, and ran for Mayor of Syracuse in 2017.\n\n==Early life and career==\nHoward Gresham Hawkins<ref name=\"father obituary\">https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2000-08-06-0008060178-story.html</ref><ref name=\"father wrestler\">http://photoarchive.lib.uchicago.edu/db.xqy?show=browse5.xml%7C2069</ref> was born in [[San Francisco]], [[California]], in 1952, and raised in nearby [[San Mateo, California|San Mateo]].<ref name=\"Tarleton\"/> His father was an attorney who was a football and wrestling student-athlete at the [[University of Chicago]] and served in the counter-intelligence unit for the [[U.S. Army]]'s [[Manhattan Project]] during [[World War II]].<ref name=\"father obituary\"/><ref name=\"father wrestler\"/> He became politically active at the age of 12, when he saw how the multiracial [[Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party]] was denied recognition at the [[1964 Democratic Convention]].<ref name=\"Tarleton\">{{cite news|url=http://indypendent.org/2014/10/28/meet-howie-hawkins-anti-cuomo|title=Meet Howie Hawkins, the Anti-Cuomo|last=Tarleton|first=John|date=October 28, 2014|work=[[The Indypendent]]|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref> According to Hawkins he was drafted in June 1972, at the age of 19, and  enlisted in the U.S. Marine Corps, despite his previous [[anti-war movement|anti-war activism]]. However, he states he was never ordered into active duty.<ref name=\"NYT2018\"/> In 1972, Hawkins campaigned for the [[Liberty Union Party]] candidate [[Bernie Sanders]] for the [[1972 United States Senate special election in Vermont|senate]] and [[1972 Vermont gubernatorial election|governor]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Another socialist for US president {{!}} Workers' Liberty |url=https://www.workersliberty.org/story/2019-11-27/another-socialist-us-president |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Workers Liberty}}</ref>\n\n===Green Party===\nIn the 1980s Hawkins joined the [[Green politics|green movement]]. In 1988, he and [[Murray Bookchin]] founded the Left Green Network \"as a radical alternative to U.S. Green liberals\", based around the principles of [[Social ecology (Bookchin)|social ecology]] and [[libertarian municipalism]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Biehl |first1=Janet |title=The Left Green Network (1988-91) |url=http://www.biehlonbookchin.com/left-green-network/ |website=Ecology or Catastrophe |accessdate=16 November 2019 |date=22 March 2015}}</ref> In the early 1990s a press conference was held in Washington, D.C., that featured Charles Betz, Joni Whitmore, Hilda Mason, and Howie Hawkins to announce the formation of the [[Greens/Green Party USA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?20897-1/official-formation-green-partyusa|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019080559/https://www.c-span.org/video/?20897-1/official-formation-green-partyusa|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-10-19|title=Official Formation of the Green Party-USA|work=c-span.org}}</ref> Later in December 1999, [[Mike Feinstein]] and Hawkins wrote the Plan for a Single National Green Party which was the plan to organize the [[Association of State Green Parties|ASGP]] and [[Greens/Green Party USA|GPUSA]] into a single [[Green Party of the United States|Green Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greenparty.org/gatheringminutes.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810052904/https://www.greenparty.org/gatheringminutes.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=2017-08-10 |title=The Greens/Green Party USA |publisher=Greenparty.org |date= |accessdate=2015-03-16}}</ref> A [[perennial candidate]], Hawkins ran in multiple New York [[2006 United States Senate election in New York|Senate]] and [[2008 United States House of Representatives elections in New York|House]] races.<ref>{{cite news|title=0-for-23: An Undeterred Green Party Candidate on His Long Losing Streak|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/19/nyregion/howie-hawkins-green-party-governor.html|access-date=2019-04-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426213550/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/19/nyregion/howie-hawkins-green-party-governor.html|archive-date=2019-04-26|url-status=live|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 19, 2018|last1=McKinley|first1=Jesse}}</ref> In [[2010 New York gubernatorial election|2010]] he surpassed the 50,000 vote requirement to stay on the ballot in the gubernatorial election and [[2014 New York gubernatorial election|four years]] later he received enough to move the Green Party line to Row D as he had taken one-third more than the [[Working Families Party]] and twice as much as the [[Independence Party of New York|Independence Party]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title=Third party's profile rises\n|url=https://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Third-party-s-profile-rises-5921969.php\n|access-date=2019-04-30\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118121710/https://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Third-party-s-profile-rises-5921969.php\n|archive-date=2018-11-18\n|url-status=live\n|date=November 28, 2014\n}}\n</ref> However, in [[2018 New York gubernatorial election|2018]] he lost 80,000 votes, but retained ballot access and was only lowered one row down to Row E.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syracuse.com/politics/2018/11/green_party_howie_hawkins_new_york_governor_2018_election.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412024252/https://www.syracuse.com/politics/2018/11/green_party_howie_hawkins_new_york_governor_2018_election.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 12, 2019|title=Howie Hawkins wins enough votes to keep Green Party status in NY|author=Breidenbach, Michelle|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2012 Green Party presidential primaries|2012]] Hawkins was approached over the possibility of running for the Green Party nomination, but declined due to his employment commitments at [[United Parcel Service|UPS]] forcing him to campaign for offices in New York at most and would interfere with a national campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/why-is-syracuse-s-howie-hawkins-running-for-president-it/article_56758623-4e45-5635-859a-859f3889612b.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410034427/https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/why-is-syracuse-s-howie-hawkins-running-for-president-it/article_56758623-4e45-5635-859a-859f3889612b.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 10, 2019|title=Why is Syracuse's Howie Hawkins running for president? 'It's hard to say no' &#124; Eye on NY &#124; auburnpub.com|date=April 10, 2019}}</ref> Following Hawkins' retirement he was approached again to run by a [[Draft (politics)|draft movement]] with a public letter addressed to him that was signed by former Green vice presidential nominees [[Cheri Honkala]] and [[Ajamu Baraka]], former Green mayoral candidate and [[Ralph Nader]]'s 2008 running mate [[Matt Gonzalez]], and other prominent Green Party members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://independentpoliticalreport.com/2019/03/sign-on-greens-urge-howie-hawkins-to-seek-presidential-nomination/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402141451/https://independentpoliticalreport.com/2019/03/sign-on-greens-urge-howie-hawkins-to-seek-presidential-nomination/|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 2, 2019|title=Sign On: Greens And Allies Urge Howie Hawkins To Seek Presidential Nomination &#124; Independent Political Report|date=April 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHawkins was accidentally listed on ballots in Minnesota as the Green Party candidate for Vice President, along with [[Jill Stein]] for President in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 general election]]. Although [[Ajamu Baraka]] was Stein's running mate on the party's national ticket, Hawkins was inadvertently placed on the Minnesota ballot due to the party using him as a stand-in before the vice-presidential candidate was chosen.<ref name=MPR>{{cite news |last=Pugmire |first=Tim |date= August 22, 2016 |title=MN ballot will show wrong Green Party veep candidate |url=http://blogs.mprnews.org/capitol-view/2016/08/mn-ballot-will-show-wrong-green-party-veep-candidate/ |newspaper=[[Minnesota Public Radio]] |access-date= August 22, 2016 }}</ref> With Hawkins listed, the Green Party ticket for [[2016 United States presidential election in Minnesota|President of the United States in Minnesota]] received nearly 37,000 votes statewide, an increase of 0.82% from the party's previous result in [[2012 United States presidential election in Minnesota|2012]].\n\n===Political positions===\nIn 1993, Hawkins favored [[anarcho-communism]] as well as [[libertarian municipalism]], as the \"best way of integrating worker's control and community control in a process of social change that ultimately yields in a marketless, moneyless, stateless cooperative commonwealth\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hawkins |first1=Howie |title=Community Control, Worker\u2019s Control and the Cooperative Commonwealth. |journal=Society and Nature |date=1993 |volume=3 |page=60 |url=http://social-ecology.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2009/12/Peter.3.Cooperative_Commonwealth.pdf}}</ref> Hawkins is also a member of the [[Industrial Workers of the World]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Howie Hawkins for 4th District Councilor - Interview by Brendan Maslauskas Dunn |url=http://howiehawkins.com/2010/index.php/interviews/399-interview-by-brendan-maslauskas-dunn |website=howiehawkins.com|last1=Dunn|first1=Brendan Maslauskas|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nHawkins disagrees with the \"party-within-the-party\" approach to the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] advocated by organisations such as the [[Democratic Socialists of America]] or by individuals such as [[Bernie Sanders]].<ref name=\"ISR\">{{cite web |last1=Hawkins |first1=Howie |title=The case for an independent Left party |url=https://isreview.org/issue/107/case-independent-left-party |website=International Socialist Review |accessdate=17 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Instead, he believes that socialists should create an independent left-wing party.<ref name=\"ISR\" />\n\nHawkins became the first politician to include the [[Green New Deal]] in their election platform when he ran for Governor of New York in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sorry Democrats, the Green Party Came Up With the Green New Deal!|last1=Stewart|first1=Andrew|work=Counter Punch|date=November 29, 2018|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2018/11/29/sorry-democrats-the-green-party-came-up-with-the-green-new-deal/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416132943/https://www.counterpunch.org/2018/11/29/sorry-democrats-the-green-party-came-up-with-the-green-new-deal/|url-status=dead|archivedate=2019-04-16}}</ref> Hawkins supports the Green Party's version of the Green New Deal that would serve as a transitional plan to a one hundred percent clean, renewable energy by 2030 utilizing a [[carbon tax]], [[Job guarantee|jobs guarantee]], free college, [[single-payer healthcare]] and a focus on using public programs.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Democrats Stole the Green Party's Best Idea |work=The New Republic|last1=Atkin|first1=Emily|date=February 22, 2019 |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/153127/democrats-stole-green-partys-best-idea|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301003909/https://newrepublic.com/article/153127/democrats-stole-green-partys-best-idea |url-status=dead |archivedate=2019-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The 'Green New Deal' isn't really that new |work=Market Watch|last1=Schroeder|first1=Robert|date=February 12, 2019 |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/the-green-new-deal-isnt-really-that-new-2019-02-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416132945/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/the-green-new-deal-isnt-really-that-new-2019-02-11 |url-status=dead |archivedate=2019-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==New York politics==\nHawkins was the [[Green Party of New York]]'s candidate for the [[2006 New York United States Senate election|United States Senate]] in the state of New York. Hawkins received 55,469 votes in the November 2006 election (during which Hillary Clinton was re-elected), for 1.2% of the total votes cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2006/general/2006_ussen.pdf |title=C:\\Documents and Settings\\hhardwick\\Desktop\\WEBSITE\\EOU\\2006 STATEWIDE JD GOV BY AD.qpw |date= |accessdate=2019-04-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Hawkins ran for the [[United States House of Representatives]] in [[New York's 25th congressional district]] on the Green Populist line. Hawkins won 9,483 votes, losing to Democrat Dan Maffei.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2008/General/USCongress08.pdf |title=Results |date=2008 |website=www.elections.ny.gov }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Green Presidential and Gubernatorial Results In New York.png|thumb|Hawkins' Gubernatorial Performance]]\n\nIn May 2010, Hawkins was nominated to run for [[2010 New York gubernatorial election|Governor of New York]] as the Green Party candidate. His campaign was also supported by the [[Socialist Party of New York]].<ref name=\"syracuse soc\"/>\n\nHawkins was critical of his Democratic opponent, [[Andrew Cuomo]], and challenged him to participate in public forums with the other gubernatorial candidates. In a ''[[New York Daily News]]'' interview, Hawkins expressed his concerns with some of Cuomo's positions:\n\n<blockquote>...  he [Cuomo] wants to solve the state budget crisis by cutting spending such as for state workers and schools. He ignores that the root cause of the problem is not spending but the huge tax cuts for the wealthy that began when he was helping his father as Governor. Instead of spending caps, we need the wealthy and Wall Street to pay their fair share.<ref>Katz, Celeste {{cite news | title=Green Party's Howie Hawkins Weighs In On Cuomo | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2010/05/green-partys-howie-hawkins-wei.html | accessdate=July 4, 2010 | location=New York | work=Daily News | first=Celeste | last=Katz | date=May 22, 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100524020740/http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2010/05/green-partys-howie-hawkins-wei.html | archivedate=May 24, 2010 | df=mdy-all }} ''The New York Daily News'', May 22, 2010</ref></blockquote>\n\nOn November 2, 2010, Hawkins received nearly 60,000 votes (1.3%), allowing the Green Party of New York to be listed on the ballot for the next four years.<ref name=\"Election 2010: Election Results\">{{cite news|title=Election 2010: Election Results |url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/results/new-york|accessdate=November 3, 2010 | work=The New York Times}} ''The New York Times''</ref><ref name=\"syracuse.com\">Mariani, John {{cite web|title=Howie Hawkins' votes for governor boost Green Party's ballot status|url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2010/11/hawkins_votes_for_governor_boo.html|accessdate=November 3, 2010|date=November 3, 2010}} ''The Post Standard'', November 3, 2010</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, Hawkins was named co-chair of the newly recognized Green Party of New York.<ref>[http://www.gp.org/press/pr-state.php?ID=375 Green Party certified as ballot qualified Party in NY; elects statewide officers] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101218220622/http://www.gp.org/press/pr-state.php?ID=375 |date=December 18, 2010 }} GPNY.org</ref>\n\nHawkins announced his candidacy for 4th District Common Councilor in Syracuse in September 2011, running as a Green Party candidate.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2011/09/howie_hawkins_to_run_for_syrac.html|title=Howie Hawkins to run for Syracuse Common Council|publisher=|accessdate=February 28, 2018|date=September 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eaglenewsonline.com/news/2011/oct/07/howie-hawkins-perennial-power-people/|title=Howie Hawkins: Perennial power to the people|date=October 7, 2011|publisher=|accessdate=February 28, 2018}}</ref> His opponent was a Democrat, Khalid Bey. Hawkins received endorsements from the Syracuse Post Standard, UNITE HERE Local 150, and the Greater Syracuse Labor Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.howiehawkins.com/2011/index.php/endorsements|title=Endorsements|website=Howie Hawkins|accessdate=February 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.syracuse.com/opinion/2011/11/our_endorsements_syracuse_comm.html|title=Our Endorsements: Syracuse Common Council|publisher=|accessdate=February 28, 2018|date=November 2011}}</ref> Hawkins planned to sponsor resolutions for state tax code reforms to require more from the state's wealthiest, and to share more revenues with cities. He also supported the establishment of a municipal development bank to provide financing for local cooperative businesses and a 0.4% \"commuter tax\" on the incomes of suburbanites working in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2011/10/syracuse_city_council_race_pit.html#comments|title=Syracuse city council race pits familiar face against party favorite|website=Syracuse|accessdate=February 28, 2018|date=October 27, 2011}}</ref> Hawkins lost the election to Bey.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.syracuse.com/news/2011/11/khalid_bey_declared_winner_in.html | title=Khalid Bey declared winner in Syracuse Common Council race after absentees ballots are counted| date=November 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn May 20, 2013, Hawkins announced that he would again run for 4th District Common Councilor in Syracuse. His opponent was incumbent [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Khalid Bey.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2013/05/live_qa_with_the_green_partys.html|title=Green Party's Howie Hawkins announces race for 4th District Syracuse city council in live chat|publisher=|accessdate=February 28, 2018|date=May 20, 2013}}</ref> On October 16, 2013, Hawkins published a fiscal position paper with mayoral candidate Kevin Bott focused on a new scaled local income tax, and the role of the state in the fiscal crisis in Syracuse. Bott and Hawkins point out that New York revenue sharing with its biggest cities has decreased from the teens to just about one percent since the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news| author= Delaney, Ryan| title=Greens call for more state aid and local income tax |url=http://wrvo.org/post/greens-call-more-state-aid-and-local-income-tax| date=Oct 17, 2013| publisher=wrvo.org| accessdate=October 17, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| author= Knauss, Tim| title=Syracuse Green Party candidates tout higher state aid, city income tax |url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2013/10/syracuse_green_party_candidates_tout_higher_state_aid_city_income_tax.html| date=Oct 16, 2013| publisher=syracuse.com| accessdate=October 17, 2013}}</ref> Hawkins lost the election to [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Bey by a vote of 1,471 to 995.<ref name=\"auto\">Knaus, Tim (November 5, 2013) [http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2013/11/two_new_faces_to_join_syracuse_common_council_if_results_hold.html \"Two new faces to join Syracuse Common Council, if results hold.\"] Syracuse Post-Standard. (Retrieved Mar 24, 2013.)</ref>\n\nOn April 9, 2014, Hawkins announced his second candidacy for [[2014 New York gubernatorial election|Governor of New York]] at the LCA Pressroom in [[Albany, New York]]. His campaign positions included a \"[[Green New Deal]]\" platform, a \"Clean Money\" system for public financing of elections, ending New York's role in the national Common Core standards, and a [[minimum wage]] increase to $15 an hour from the then-current $8 an hour in New York.<ref>{{cite news| author=Gormley, Michael| title=Green Party candidate for NY governor calls for $15-an-hour minimum wage |url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle-newsday-blogs-long-island-new-york-national-politics-1.812042/green-party-candidate-for-ny-governor-calls-for-15-an-hour-minimum-wage-1.7655298?| date=April 9, 2014| publisher=newsday.com| accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> Hawkins' running mate for [[Lt. Governor]] was New York City educator and union activist [[Brian Jones (activist)|Brian Jones]].<ref>Moody, Richard {{cite web|title=Green party solidifies ticket|url=http://www.legislativegazette.com/Articles-Top-Stories-c-2014-05-27-88072.113122-Green-party-solidifies-ticket.html}} legislativegazette.com| accessdate=May 27, 2014</ref> Hawkins and the Green Party received 184,419 votes (4.8% of the vote), which moved the [[Green Party of New York|Green Party]] up to the fourth line on state ballots for the next four years (surpassing the Working Families and Independence parties).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2014/general/2014Governor.pdf |title=Results |date=2014 |website=www.elections.ny.gov }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Hawkins ran for Syracuse City [[Auditor]] against incumbent Marty Masterpole. Hawkins noted that Masterpole had filed only two financial audits, and criticized him for auditing city skating rinks and golf courses while the city suffered from high poverty, failing infrastructure and struggling schools.<ref>Knauss, Tim {{cite web|title=Race for Syracuse city auditor heats up: Are 4 audits a year enough? |url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2015/10/race_for_syracuse_city_auditor_heats_up_are_4_audits_a_year_enough.html|date=October 9, 2015}} ''Syracuse.com '', October 9, 2015</ref> Former District 2 city councilor Pat Hogan suggested to Hawkins that he should run for auditor, stating, \"I'm not turning Green ... I am more concerned about the city than the party. The auditor is supposed to be a [[Consumer organization|watchdog]] on the city budgets and Marty isn't doing any watching. There's a dearth of independence in city government.\"<ref>Shepperd, Walt {{cite web|title=Green Wants to Watch City's Greenbacks |url=http://www.syracusenewtimes.com/green-wants-to-watch-citys-greenbacks/|date=October 14, 2015}} ''Syracuse New Times '', October 14, 2015</ref> Hawkins lost the election, winning 35 percent of the vote.<ref name=\"O'Brien, John 2015\">O'Brien, John (November 3, 2015) [http://www.syracuse.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/11/syracuse_auditor_marty_masterpole_howie_hawkins.html \"Syracuse auditor: Marty Masterpole beats Howie Hawkins.\"] Syracuse.com. (Retrieved 11-15-2015).</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Hawkins ran for Mayor of Syracuse as a Green Party candidate to replace outgoing mayor Stephanie Miner. One of his central campaign points was to restore the [[Erie Canal]] through Downtown Syracuse to help aide in the revitalization of the neighborhood, with the belief that 'Cities that capitalize on their waterways tend to have more vibrant downtowns<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.syracuse.com/news/2017/10/5_novel_policies_howie_hawkins_thinks_will_fix_a_broken_syracuse.html|title=Let's bring back the Erie Canal: 5 policies Howie Hawkins proposes to fix Syracuse|date=2017-10-31|website=syracuse|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>'. Hawkins won 4.1% of the vote (excluding write-ins) and lost to independent Ben Walsh (54,4%, excluding write-ins),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.syracuse.com/politics/2017/11/election_2017_complete_results_for_onondaga_county.html|title=Election 2017: Results for Syracuse mayor, other Onondaga County races|date=2017-11-08|website=syracuse|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> the first independent in the City's history.\n\nOn April 12, 2018, Hawkins announced his third run for [[2018 New York gubernatorial election|Governor of New York]] on the Green Party line. Hawkins and running mate Jia Lee received 95,716 votes (1.7%).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nyenr.elections.ny.gov/ |title=NYS Board of Elections Unofficial Election Night Results |access-date=November 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120174014/https://nyenr.elections.ny.gov/ |archive-date=November 20, 2018 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==2020 presidential campaign==\n{{Main|Howie Hawkins 2020 presidential campaign}}\n\nThe 2020 presidential campaign of Howie Hawkins was informally launched on April 3, 2019 when Hawkins announced the formation of an [[exploratory committee]]. He formally announced his campaign on May 28, 2019, to seek the Green Party nomination for the presidency of the United States in the 2020 presidential election and later the [[Socialist Party USA]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Howie Hawkins, Syracuse resident, exploring run for Green Party presidential nod|url=https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/howie-hawkins-syracuse-resident-exploring-run-for-green-party-presidential/article_1bc6e864-e446-566c-a36e-690150d2422c.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403203904/https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/howie-hawkins-syracuse-resident-exploring-run-for-green-party-presidential/article_1bc6e864-e446-566c-a36e-690150d2422c.html|archivedate=2019-04-03|access-date=2019-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Howie Hawkins, Syracuse resident, exploring run for Green Party presidential nod|url=https://www.timesunion.com/news/article/Howie-Hawkins-will-seek-Green-nomination-for-13900737.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529005905/https://www.timesunion.com/news/article/Howie-Hawkins-will-seek-Green-nomination-for-13900737.php|archivedate=2019-05-29|access-date=2019-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn October 26, 2019, Hawkins won the nomination of the Socialist Party USA in his effort to unite smaller left-wing parties together.<ref>{{cite web|title=Howie Hawkins wins Socialist Party USA nomination for 2020 presidential race|url=https://www.localsyr.com/news/your-local-election-hq/howie-hawkins-wins-socialist-party-usa-nomination-for-2020-presidential-race/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104051752/https://www.localsyr.com/news/your-local-election-hq/howie-hawkins-wins-socialist-party-usa-nomination-for-2020-presidential-race/|archivedate=2019-11-04|access-date=2019-10-28|url-status=live}}</ref> In November, Hawkins won the nomination of [[Solidarity (United States)|Solidarity]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Howie Hawkins for President |url=https://solidarity-us.org/atc/203/hawins-for-president/ |website=Solidarity |language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Background====\nIn the 1980s Hawkins joined the [[Green politics|green movement]] and in the early 1990s a press conference was held in Washington, D.C., that featured Charles Betz, Joni Whitmore, Hilda Mason, and Howie Hawkins to announce the formation of the [[Greens/Green Party USA]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Official Formation of the Green Party-USA|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?20897-1/official-formation-green-partyusa|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019080559/https://www.c-span.org/video/?20897-1%2Fofficial-formation-green-partyusa|archivedate=October 19, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> Later in December 1999, [[Mike Feinstein]] and Hawkins wrote the Plan for a Single National Green Party which was the plan to organize the [[Association of State Green Parties|ASGP]] and [[Greens/Green Party USA|GPUSA]] into a single [[Green Party of the United States|Green Party]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Greens/Green Party USA|url=https://www.greenparty.org/gatheringminutes.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810052904/https://www.greenparty.org/gatheringminutes.php|archivedate=2017-08-10|url-status=live}}</ref> Over the next decade he would run in multiple New York [[2006 United States Senate election in New York|Senate]] and [[2008 United States House of Representatives elections in New York|House]] races.<ref>{{cite web|title=0-for-23: An Undeterred Green Party Candidate on His Long Losing Streak|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/19/nyregion/howie-hawkins-green-party-governor.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426213550/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/19/nyregion/howie-hawkins-green-party-governor.html|archivedate=2019-04-26|url-status=live}}</ref> In [[2010 New York gubernatorial election|2010]] he surpassed the 50,000 vote requirement to stay on the ballot in the gubernatorial election and [[2014 New York gubernatorial election|four years]] later he received enough to move the Green Party line to Row D as he had taken one-third more than the [[Working Families Party]] and twice as much as the [[Independence Party of New York|Independence Party]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Third party's profile rises|url=https://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Third-party-s-profile-rises-5921969.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118121710/https://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Third-party-s-profile-rises-5921969.php|archivedate=2018-11-18|url-status=live}}</ref> However, in [[2018 New York gubernatorial election|2018]] he lost 80,000 votes, but retained ballot access and was only lowered one row down to Row E.<ref>{{cite web|title=Howie Hawkins wins enough votes to keep Green Party status in NY|url=https://www.syracuse.com/politics/2018/11/green_party_howie_hawkins_new_york_governor_2018_election.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412024252/https://www.syracuse.com/politics/2018/11/green_party_howie_hawkins_new_york_governor_2018_election.html|archivedate=2019-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref> In [[2012 Green Party presidential primaries|2012]] Hawkins was approached over the possibility of running for the Green Party nomination, but declined due to his employment commitments at [[United Parcel Service|UPS]] forcing him to campaign for offices in New York at most and would interfere with a national campaign.<ref>{{cite web|title=Why is Syracuse's Howie Hawkins running for president? 'It's hard to say no'|url=https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/why-is-syracuse-s-howie-hawkins-running-for-president-it/article_56758623-4e45-5635-859a-859f3889612b.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410034427/https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/why-is-syracuse-s-howie-hawkins-running-for-president-it/article_56758623-4e45-5635-859a-859f3889612b.html|archivedate=2019-04-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHowever, following Hawkins' retirement he was approached again to run by a draft movement with a public letter addressed to him that was signed by former Green vice presidential nominees [[Cheri Honkala]] and [[Ajamu Baraka]], former Green mayoral candidate and [[Ralph Nader|Nader's]] 2008 running mate [[Matt Gonzalez]], and other prominent Green Party members.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sign On: Greens And Allies Urge Howie Hawkins To Seek Presidential Nomination|url=https://independentpoliticalreport.com/2019/03/sign-on-greens-urge-howie-hawkins-to-seek-presidential-nomination/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402141451/https://independentpoliticalreport.com/2019/03/sign-on-greens-urge-howie-hawkins-to-seek-presidential-nomination/|archivedate=2019-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Campaign====\n{{Main|Howie Hawkins 2020 presidential campaign}}\n\nOn April 3, 2019, Hawkins announced that he was forming an [[exploratory committee]] to prepare for a potential candidacy for the Green Party [[2020 United States presidential election|2020]] [[2020 Green Party presidential primaries|presidential nomination]] and later Hawkins formally launched his campaign on May 28, 2019, in [[Brooklyn |Brooklyn, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/howie-hawkins-syracuse-resident-exploring-run-for-green-party-presidential/article_1bc6e864-e446-566c-a36e-690150d2422c.html|title=Howie Hawkins, Syracuse resident, exploring run for Green Party presidential nod|first=Robert Harding|last=robert.harding@lee.net|date=|website=Auburn Citizen|accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://howiehawkins.us/|title=Howie Hawkins for President Exploratory Committee - A Green Ecosocialist for President|author=|date=March 29, 2019|publisher=|accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesunion.com/news/article/Howie-Hawkins-will-seek-Green-nomination-for-13900737.php|title=Howie Hawkins will seek Green nomination for president|date=May 28, 2019|website=Times Union|access-date=June 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn August 23, 2019, the Hawkins campaign announced they had met the requisite [[Presidential election campaign fund checkoff|federal matching funds]] for [[California]] and [[New York State|New York]].<ref>{{cite tweet|last=Hawkins|first=Howie|user=HowieHawkins20|number=1164962792375349248|date=23 August 2019|title=Thank you, @cagreenparty|accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref> The campaign must receive $5,000 from residents, with no more than $250 counted for each contribution, in at least 20 states to qualify for the funds. Only his campaign and Steve Bullock's applied for primary season matching funds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Montana Governor Steve Bullock Will Apply for Primary Season Matching Funds|url=https://ballot-access.org/2019/09/30/montana-governor-steve-bullock-will-apply-for-primary-season-matching-funds/|website=Ballot Access News|last1=Winger|first1=Richard|date=September 30, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002132702/http://ballot-access.org/2019/09/30/montana-governor-steve-bullock-will-apply-for-primary-season-matching-funds/|archivedate=2019-10-02|access-date=2019-09-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHawkins received the nomination of the [[Socialist Party USA]] on October 26, 2019.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=SPofUSA|number=1188213871359778816|title=The Socialist Party is excited to announce Howie Hawkins as its presidential nominee for the 2020 election!|date=October 26, 2019|author=[[Socialist Party USA]]|accessdate=October 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Main|Electoral history of Howie Hawkins}}\n\n==Publications==\n* {{cite book |last1=Hawkins |first1=Howard |title=Independent Politics: The Green Party Strategy Debate |date=2006 |publisher=Haymarket Books |isbn=978-1-931859-30-1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rxqIAAAAMAAJ&q |language=en}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Howie |first1=Hawkins |title=The Case For An Independent Left Party: From The Bottom Up |date=2020}}\n* [https://newpol.org/authors/hawkins-howie/ Howie Hawkins] [[New Politics (magazine)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://howiehawkins.us/ Howie Hawkins 2020 Presidential Campaign Website]\n*[http://www.howiehawkins.org/ Howie Hawkins 2014 Campaign Website]\n*[http://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/syracusegreens/pages/326/attachments/original/1381936146/The_Once_and_Future_Solution___position_paper.pdf \"Restore State Revenue Sharing Funded by Progressive Taxation: The Once and Future Solution to the City's Fiscal Crisis\"], position paper, October 16, 2013\n*[http://www.ontheissues.org/Senate/Howie_Hawkins.htm Howie Hawkins On The Issues, (2006)]\n*[https://www.amazon.com/dp/1931859302/ Independent Politics: The Green Party Strategy Debate], by Howie Hawkins, Haymarket Books, 2006.\n{{United States presidential election, 2020}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box | before=none| title=[[Green Party (United States)|Green Party]] Candidate for [[New York State Comptroller]] | years= 1998 and 2002 | after=[[Julia Willebrand]]}}\n{{succession box|before=[[David McReynolds]] | title=[[Green Party (United States)|Green Party]] Candidate for [[List of United States Senators from New York|United States Senator from New York]]|years= 2006|after=Cecile Lawrence}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Malachy McCourt]]| title=[[Green Party (United States)|Green Party]] Candidate for [[New York State Governor]] | years= 2010, 2014, 2018 | after=most recent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hawkins, Howie}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2016 United States vice-presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Activists from Syracuse, New York]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013nuclear power activists]]\n[[Category:American democratic socialists]]\n[[Category:Citizens Party (United States) politicians]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:Green Party of the United States politicians]]\n[[Category:Industrial Workers of the World members]]\n[[Category:Labor Party (United States, 1996) politicians]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Members of Solidarity (United States)]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Greens]]\n[[Category:Peace and Freedom Party politicians]]\n[[Category:People from San Mateo, California]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Syracuse, New York]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 United States elections]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Howie Hawkins\n|image       = Hawkins 2010.jpg\n|birth_name = Howard Gresham Hawkins\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1952|12|8}}\n|birth_place = [[San Francisco]], [[California]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Green Party of the United States|Green]]\n|otherparty  = [[Socialist Party USA|Socialist]] (Affiliated)<ref name=\"syracuse soc\">Mariani, John. {{cite web |title=Socialists back Howie Hawkins' Green bid for governor |url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2010/06/socialists_back_howie_hawkins.html |accessdate=June 15, 2010 |date=June 14, 2010}} ''The Syracuse Post Standard'', Monday June 14, 2010</ref>\n|education   = [[Dartmouth College]]\n|allegiance  = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch      = {{flag|United States Marine Corps}}\n}}{{Howie Hawkins series}}\n'''Howard Gresham Hawkins''' (born December 8, 1952) is an American trade unionist and [[political activism|activist]] from [[New York (state)|New York]]. A co-founder of the [[Green Party of the United States]], Hawkins is [[Howie Hawkins 2020 presidential campaign|seeking the party's nomination for President in 2020]]. His primary campaign issues include enacting an [[eco-socialism|eco-socialist]] [[Green New Deal]], which he first proposed in 2010, and building a viable, independent working-class political and social movement in opposition to the Democratic and Republican parties and capitalism in general.<ref name=\"IndependentPolitics2006\">{{cite book |last1=Hawkins |first1=Howie |title=Independent politics : the Green Party strategy debate |date=April 11, 2006 |publisher=Haymarket Books |isbn=9781931859301 |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nHawkins has played leading roles in [[Veterans for Peace|anti-war]],<ref name=\"VetsForPeace2016\">{{cite news |title=U.S. Vets Lead Civil Disobedience Action at Crestwood to Protest Seneca Lake Gas Storage |url=https://www.veteransforpeace.org/who-we-are/member-highlights/2016/01/27/us-vets-lead-civil-disobedience-action-crestwood-protest-sen |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=www.veteransforpeace.org |date=27 January 2016 |language=en}}</ref> [[Clamshell Alliance|anti-nuclear]],<ref name=\"NYT2018\">{{cite news |last1=McKinley |first1=Jesse |title=0-for-23: An Undeterred Green Party Candidate on His Long Losing Streak |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/19/nyregion/howie-hawkins-green-party-governor.html |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=19 October 2018}}</ref> and pro-worker movements since the 1960s. Hawkins is a retired [[International Brotherhood of Teamsters|teamster]] and construction worker; from 2001 until his retirement in 2017, Hawkins worked the night shift unloading trucks for [[United Parcel Service|UPS]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baker |first1=Chris |title=Syracuse\u2019s Howie Hawkins mulls a run for president |url=https://www.syracuse.com/politics/2019/04/syracuses-howie-hawkins-mulls-a-run-for-president-with-green-party.html |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=syracuse |date=3 April 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"EugeneWeekly\">{{cite news |title=It Ain\u2019t Easy Being Green |url=https://www.eugeneweekly.com/2020/01/09/it-aint-easy-being-green/ |accessdate=16 March 2020 |work=Eugene Weekly |date=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nHawkins has run for office on several occasions, all unsuccessfully. He was [[Green Party of New York|New York's Green Party]] candidate for the [[2006 New York United States Senate election|U.S. Senate]] in 2006. In 2010, Hawkins ran as the Green Party's candidate for [[2010 New York gubernatorial election|Governor of New York]], which restored ballot status for the party when it received more than the necessary 50,000 votes. In 2014, Hawkins ran again for the same office and received five percent of the vote. Hawkins ran a third time for Governor of New York in 2018, and ran for Mayor of Syracuse in 2017.\n\n==Early life and career==\nHoward Gresham Hawkins<ref name=\"father obituary\">https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2000-08-06-0008060178-story.html</ref><ref name=\"father wrestler\">http://photoarchive.lib.uchicago.edu/db.xqy?show=browse5.xml%7C2069</ref> was born in [[San Francisco]], [[California]], in 1952, and raised in nearby [[San Mateo, California|San Mateo]].<ref name=\"Tarleton\"/> His father was an attorney who was a football and wrestling student-athlete at the [[University of Chicago]] and served in the counter-intelligence unit for the [[U.S. Army]]'s [[Manhattan Project]] during [[World War II]].<ref name=\"father obituary\"/><ref name=\"father wrestler\"/> He became politically active at the age of 12, when he saw how the multiracial [[Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party]] was denied recognition at the [[1964 Democratic Convention]].<ref name=\"Tarleton\">{{cite news|url=http://indypendent.org/2014/10/28/meet-howie-hawkins-anti-cuomo|title=Meet Howie Hawkins, the Anti-Cuomo|last=Tarleton|first=John|date=October 28, 2014|work=[[The Indypendent]]|accessdate=30 October 2014}}</ref> According to Hawkins he was drafted in June 1972, at the age of 19, and  enlisted in the U.S. Marine Corps, despite his previous [[anti-war movement|anti-war activism]]. However, he states he was never ordered into active duty.<ref name=\"NYT2018\"/> In 1972, Hawkins campaigned for the [[Liberty Union Party]] candidate [[Bernie Sanders]] for the [[1972 United States Senate special election in Vermont|senate]] and [[1972 Vermont gubernatorial election|governor]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Another socialist for US president {{!}} Workers' Liberty |url=https://www.workersliberty.org/story/2019-11-27/another-socialist-us-president |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Workers Liberty}}</ref>\n\n===Green Party===\nIn the 1980s Hawkins joined the [[Green politics|green movement]]. In 1988, he and [[Murray Bookchin]] founded the Left Green Network \"as a radical alternative to U.S. Green liberals\", based around the principles of [[Social ecology (Bookchin)|social ecology]] and [[libertarian municipalism]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Biehl |first1=Janet |title=The Left Green Network (1988-91) |url=http://www.biehlonbookchin.com/left-green-network/ |website=Ecology or Catastrophe |accessdate=16 November 2019 |date=22 March 2015}}</ref> In the early 1990s a press conference was held in Washington, D.C., that featured Charles Betz, Joni Whitmore, Hilda Mason, and Howie Hawkins to announce the formation of the [[Greens/Green Party USA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?20897-1/official-formation-green-partyusa|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019080559/https://www.c-span.org/video/?20897-1/official-formation-green-partyusa|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-10-19|title=Official Formation of the Green Party-USA|work=c-span.org}}</ref> Later in December 1999, [[Mike Feinstein]] and Hawkins wrote the Plan for a Single National Green Party which was the plan to organize the [[Association of State Green Parties|ASGP]] and [[Greens/Green Party USA|GPUSA]] into a single [[Green Party of the United States|Green Party]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.greenparty.org/gatheringminutes.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810052904/https://www.greenparty.org/gatheringminutes.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=2017-08-10 |title=The Greens/Green Party USA |publisher=Greenparty.org |date= |accessdate=2015-03-16}}</ref> A [[perennial candidate]], Hawkins ran in multiple New York [[2006 United States Senate election in New York|Senate]] and [[2008 United States House of Representatives elections in New York|House]] races.<ref>{{cite news|title=0-for-23: An Undeterred Green Party Candidate on His Long Losing Streak|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/19/nyregion/howie-hawkins-green-party-governor.html|access-date=2019-04-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426213550/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/19/nyregion/howie-hawkins-green-party-governor.html|archive-date=2019-04-26|url-status=live|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 19, 2018|last1=McKinley|first1=Jesse}}</ref> In [[2010 New York gubernatorial election|2010]] he surpassed the 50,000 vote requirement to stay on the ballot in the gubernatorial election and [[2014 New York gubernatorial election|four years]] later he received enough to move the Green Party line to Row D as he had taken one-third more than the [[Working Families Party]] and twice as much as the [[Independence Party of New York|Independence Party]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n|title=Third party's profile rises\n|url=https://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Third-party-s-profile-rises-5921969.php\n|access-date=2019-04-30\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118121710/https://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Third-party-s-profile-rises-5921969.php\n|archive-date=2018-11-18\n|url-status=live\n|date=November 28, 2014\n}}\n</ref> However, in [[2018 New York gubernatorial election|2018]] he lost 80,000 votes, but retained ballot access and was only lowered one row down to Row E.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syracuse.com/politics/2018/11/green_party_howie_hawkins_new_york_governor_2018_election.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412024252/https://www.syracuse.com/politics/2018/11/green_party_howie_hawkins_new_york_governor_2018_election.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 12, 2019|title=Howie Hawkins wins enough votes to keep Green Party status in NY|author=Breidenbach, Michelle|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=November 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2012 Green Party presidential primaries|2012]] Hawkins was approached over the possibility of running for the Green Party nomination, but declined due to his employment commitments at [[United Parcel Service|UPS]] forcing him to campaign for offices in New York at most and would interfere with a national campaign.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/why-is-syracuse-s-howie-hawkins-running-for-president-it/article_56758623-4e45-5635-859a-859f3889612b.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410034427/https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/why-is-syracuse-s-howie-hawkins-running-for-president-it/article_56758623-4e45-5635-859a-859f3889612b.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 10, 2019|title=Why is Syracuse's Howie Hawkins running for president? 'It's hard to say no' &#124; Eye on NY &#124; auburnpub.com|date=April 10, 2019}}</ref> Following Hawkins' retirement he was approached again to run by a [[Draft (politics)|draft movement]] with a public letter addressed to him that was signed by former Green vice presidential nominees [[Cheri Honkala]] and [[Ajamu Baraka]], former Green mayoral candidate and [[Ralph Nader]]'s 2008 running mate [[Matt Gonzalez]], and other prominent Green Party members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://independentpoliticalreport.com/2019/03/sign-on-greens-urge-howie-hawkins-to-seek-presidential-nomination/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402141451/https://independentpoliticalreport.com/2019/03/sign-on-greens-urge-howie-hawkins-to-seek-presidential-nomination/|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 2, 2019|title=Sign On: Greens And Allies Urge Howie Hawkins To Seek Presidential Nomination &#124; Independent Political Report|date=April 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHawkins was accidentally listed on ballots in Minnesota as the Green Party candidate for Vice President, along with [[Jill Stein]] for President in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 general election]]. Although [[Ajamu Baraka]] was Stein's running mate on the party's national ticket, Hawkins was inadvertently placed on the Minnesota ballot due to the party using him as a stand-in before the vice-presidential candidate was chosen.<ref name=MPR>{{cite news |last=Pugmire |first=Tim |date= August 22, 2016 |title=MN ballot will show wrong Green Party veep candidate |url=http://blogs.mprnews.org/capitol-view/2016/08/mn-ballot-will-show-wrong-green-party-veep-candidate/ |newspaper=[[Minnesota Public Radio]] |access-date= August 22, 2016 }}</ref> With Hawkins listed, the Green Party ticket for [[2016 United States presidential election in Minnesota|President of the United States in Minnesota]] received nearly 37,000 votes statewide, an increase of 0.82% from the party's previous result in [[2012 United States presidential election in Minnesota|2012]].\n\n===Political positions===\nIn 1993, Hawkins favored [[anarcho-communism]] as well as [[libertarian municipalism]], as the \"best way of integrating worker's control and community control in a process of social change that ultimately yields in a marketless, moneyless, stateless cooperative commonwealth\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hawkins |first1=Howie |title=Community Control, Worker\u2019s Control and the Cooperative Commonwealth. |journal=Society and Nature |date=1993 |volume=3 |page=60 |url=http://social-ecology.org/wp/wp-content/uploads/2009/12/Peter.3.Cooperative_Commonwealth.pdf}}</ref> Hawkins is also a member of the [[Industrial Workers of the World]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Howie Hawkins for 4th District Councilor - Interview by Brendan Maslauskas Dunn |url=http://howiehawkins.com/2010/index.php/interviews/399-interview-by-brendan-maslauskas-dunn |website=howiehawkins.com|last1=Dunn|first1=Brendan Maslauskas|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nHawkins disagrees with the \"party-within-the-party\" approach to the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] advocated by organisations such as the [[Democratic Socialists of America]] or by individuals such as [[Bernie Sanders]].<ref name=\"ISR\">{{cite web |last1=Hawkins |first1=Howie |title=The case for an independent Left party |url=https://isreview.org/issue/107/case-independent-left-party |website=International Socialist Review |accessdate=17 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Instead, he believes that socialists should create an independent left-wing party.<ref name=\"ISR\" />\n\nHawkins became the first politician to include the [[Green New Deal]] in their election platform when he ran for Governor of New York in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sorry Democrats, the Green Party Came Up With the Green New Deal!|last1=Stewart|first1=Andrew|work=Counter Punch|date=November 29, 2018|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2018/11/29/sorry-democrats-the-green-party-came-up-with-the-green-new-deal/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416132943/https://www.counterpunch.org/2018/11/29/sorry-democrats-the-green-party-came-up-with-the-green-new-deal/|url-status=dead|archivedate=2019-04-16}}</ref> Hawkins supports the Green Party's version of the Green New Deal that would serve as a transitional plan to a one hundred percent clean, renewable energy by 2030 utilizing a [[carbon tax]], [[Job guarantee|jobs guarantee]], free college, [[single-payer healthcare]] and a focus on using public programs.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Democrats Stole the Green Party's Best Idea |work=The New Republic|last1=Atkin|first1=Emily|date=February 22, 2019 |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/153127/democrats-stole-green-partys-best-idea|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190301003909/https://newrepublic.com/article/153127/democrats-stole-green-partys-best-idea |url-status=dead |archivedate=2019-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The 'Green New Deal' isn't really that new |work=Market Watch|last1=Schroeder|first1=Robert|date=February 12, 2019 |url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/the-green-new-deal-isnt-really-that-new-2019-02-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416132945/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/the-green-new-deal-isnt-really-that-new-2019-02-11 |url-status=dead |archivedate=2019-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==New York politics==\nHawkins was the [[Green Party of New York]]'s candidate for the [[2006 New York United States Senate election|United States Senate]] in the state of New York. Hawkins received 55,469 votes in the November 2006 election (during which Hillary Clinton was re-elected), for 1.2% of the total votes cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2006/general/2006_ussen.pdf |title=C:\\Documents and Settings\\hhardwick\\Desktop\\WEBSITE\\EOU\\2006 STATEWIDE JD GOV BY AD.qpw |date= |accessdate=2019-04-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Hawkins ran for the [[United States House of Representatives]] in [[New York's 25th congressional district]] on the Green Populist line. Hawkins won 9,483 votes, losing to Democrat Dan Maffei.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2008/General/USCongress08.pdf |title=Results |date=2008 |website=www.elections.ny.gov }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Green Presidential and Gubernatorial Results In New York.png|thumb|Hawkins' Gubernatorial Performance]]\n\nIn May 2010, Hawkins was nominated to run for [[2010 New York gubernatorial election|Governor of New York]] as the Green Party candidate. His campaign was also supported by the [[Socialist Party of New York]].<ref name=\"syracuse soc\"/>\n\nHawkins was critical of his Democratic opponent, [[Andrew Cuomo]], and challenged him to participate in public forums with the other gubernatorial candidates. In a ''[[New York Daily News]]'' interview, Hawkins expressed his concerns with some of Cuomo's positions:\n\n<blockquote>...  he [Cuomo] wants to solve the state budget crisis by cutting spending such as for state workers and schools. He ignores that the root cause of the problem is not spending but the huge tax cuts for the wealthy that began when he was helping his father as Governor. Instead of spending caps, we need the wealthy and Wall Street to pay their fair share.<ref>Katz, Celeste {{cite news | title=Green Party's Howie Hawkins Weighs In On Cuomo | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2010/05/green-partys-howie-hawkins-wei.html | accessdate=July 4, 2010 | location=New York | work=Daily News | first=Celeste | last=Katz | date=May 22, 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100524020740/http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/dailypolitics/2010/05/green-partys-howie-hawkins-wei.html | archivedate=May 24, 2010 | df=mdy-all }} ''The New York Daily News'', May 22, 2010</ref></blockquote>\n\nOn November 2, 2010, Hawkins received nearly 60,000 votes (1.3%), allowing the Green Party of New York to be listed on the ballot for the next four years.<ref name=\"Election 2010: Election Results\">{{cite news|title=Election 2010: Election Results |url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/results/new-york|accessdate=November 3, 2010 | work=The New York Times}} ''The New York Times''</ref><ref name=\"syracuse.com\">Mariani, John {{cite web|title=Howie Hawkins' votes for governor boost Green Party's ballot status|url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2010/11/hawkins_votes_for_governor_boo.html|accessdate=November 3, 2010|date=November 3, 2010}} ''The Post Standard'', November 3, 2010</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, Hawkins was named co-chair of the newly recognized Green Party of New York.<ref>[http://www.gp.org/press/pr-state.php?ID=375 Green Party certified as ballot qualified Party in NY; elects statewide officers] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101218220622/http://www.gp.org/press/pr-state.php?ID=375 |date=December 18, 2010 }} GPNY.org</ref>\n\nHawkins announced his candidacy for 4th District Common Councilor in Syracuse in September 2011, running as a Green Party candidate.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2011/09/howie_hawkins_to_run_for_syrac.html|title=Howie Hawkins to run for Syracuse Common Council|publisher=|accessdate=February 28, 2018|date=September 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eaglenewsonline.com/news/2011/oct/07/howie-hawkins-perennial-power-people/|title=Howie Hawkins: Perennial power to the people|date=October 7, 2011|publisher=|accessdate=February 28, 2018}}</ref> His opponent was a Democrat, Khalid Bey. Hawkins received endorsements from the Syracuse Post Standard, UNITE HERE Local 150, and the Greater Syracuse Labor Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.howiehawkins.com/2011/index.php/endorsements|title=Endorsements|website=Howie Hawkins|accessdate=February 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.syracuse.com/opinion/2011/11/our_endorsements_syracuse_comm.html|title=Our Endorsements: Syracuse Common Council|publisher=|accessdate=February 28, 2018|date=November 2011}}</ref> Hawkins planned to sponsor resolutions for state tax code reforms to require more from the state's wealthiest, and to share more revenues with cities. He also supported the establishment of a municipal development bank to provide financing for local cooperative businesses and a 0.4% \"commuter tax\" on the incomes of suburbanites working in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2011/10/syracuse_city_council_race_pit.html#comments|title=Syracuse city council race pits familiar face against party favorite|website=Syracuse|accessdate=February 28, 2018|date=October 27, 2011}}</ref> Hawkins lost the election to Bey.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.syracuse.com/news/2011/11/khalid_bey_declared_winner_in.html | title=Khalid Bey declared winner in Syracuse Common Council race after absentees ballots are counted| date=November 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn May 20, 2013, Hawkins announced that he would again run for 4th District Common Councilor in Syracuse. His opponent was incumbent [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Khalid Bey.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2013/05/live_qa_with_the_green_partys.html|title=Green Party's Howie Hawkins announces race for 4th District Syracuse city council in live chat|publisher=|accessdate=February 28, 2018|date=May 20, 2013}}</ref> On October 16, 2013, Hawkins published a fiscal position paper with mayoral candidate Kevin Bott focused on a new scaled local income tax, and the role of the state in the fiscal crisis in Syracuse. Bott and Hawkins point out that New York revenue sharing with its biggest cities has decreased from the teens to just about one percent since the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news| author= Delaney, Ryan| title=Greens call for more state aid and local income tax |url=http://wrvo.org/post/greens-call-more-state-aid-and-local-income-tax| date=Oct 17, 2013| publisher=wrvo.org| accessdate=October 17, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| author= Knauss, Tim| title=Syracuse Green Party candidates tout higher state aid, city income tax |url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2013/10/syracuse_green_party_candidates_tout_higher_state_aid_city_income_tax.html| date=Oct 16, 2013| publisher=syracuse.com| accessdate=October 17, 2013}}</ref> Hawkins lost the election to [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] Bey by a vote of 1,471 to 995.<ref name=\"auto\">Knaus, Tim (November 5, 2013) [http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2013/11/two_new_faces_to_join_syracuse_common_council_if_results_hold.html \"Two new faces to join Syracuse Common Council, if results hold.\"] Syracuse Post-Standard. (Retrieved Mar 24, 2013.)</ref>\n\nOn April 9, 2014, Hawkins announced his second candidacy for [[2014 New York gubernatorial election|Governor of New York]] at the LCA Pressroom in [[Albany, New York]]. His campaign positions included a \"[[Green New Deal]]\" platform, a \"Clean Money\" system for public financing of elections, ending New York's role in the national Common Core standards, and a [[minimum wage]] increase to $15 an hour from the then-current $8 an hour in New York.<ref>{{cite news| author=Gormley, Michael| title=Green Party candidate for NY governor calls for $15-an-hour minimum wage |url=http://www.newsday.com/long-island/politics/spin-cycle-newsday-blogs-long-island-new-york-national-politics-1.812042/green-party-candidate-for-ny-governor-calls-for-15-an-hour-minimum-wage-1.7655298?| date=April 9, 2014| publisher=newsday.com| accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> Hawkins' running mate for [[Lt. Governor]] was New York City educator and union activist [[Brian Jones (activist)|Brian Jones]].<ref>Moody, Richard {{cite web|title=Green party solidifies ticket|url=http://www.legislativegazette.com/Articles-Top-Stories-c-2014-05-27-88072.113122-Green-party-solidifies-ticket.html}} legislativegazette.com| accessdate=May 27, 2014</ref> Hawkins and the Green Party received 184,419 votes (4.8% of the vote), which moved the [[Green Party of New York|Green Party]] up to the fourth line on state ballots for the next four years (surpassing the Working Families and Independence parties).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elections.ny.gov/NYSBOE/elections/2014/general/2014Governor.pdf |title=Results |date=2014 |website=www.elections.ny.gov }}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Hawkins ran for Syracuse City [[Auditor]] against incumbent Marty Masterpole. Hawkins noted that Masterpole had filed only two financial audits, and criticized him for auditing city skating rinks and golf courses while the city suffered from high poverty, failing infrastructure and struggling schools.<ref>Knauss, Tim {{cite web|title=Race for Syracuse city auditor heats up: Are 4 audits a year enough? |url=http://www.syracuse.com/news/index.ssf/2015/10/race_for_syracuse_city_auditor_heats_up_are_4_audits_a_year_enough.html|date=October 9, 2015}} ''Syracuse.com '', October 9, 2015</ref> Former District 2 city councilor Pat Hogan suggested to Hawkins that he should run for auditor, stating, \"I'm not turning Green ... I am more concerned about the city than the party. The auditor is supposed to be a [[Consumer organization|watchdog]] on the city budgets and Marty isn't doing any watching. There's a dearth of independence in city government.\"<ref>Shepperd, Walt {{cite web|title=Green Wants to Watch City's Greenbacks |url=http://www.syracusenewtimes.com/green-wants-to-watch-citys-greenbacks/|date=October 14, 2015}} ''Syracuse New Times '', October 14, 2015</ref> Hawkins lost the election, winning 35 percent of the vote.<ref name=\"O'Brien, John 2015\">O'Brien, John (November 3, 2015) [http://www.syracuse.com/politics/index.ssf/2015/11/syracuse_auditor_marty_masterpole_howie_hawkins.html \"Syracuse auditor: Marty Masterpole beats Howie Hawkins.\"] Syracuse.com. (Retrieved 11-15-2015).</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Hawkins ran for Mayor of Syracuse as a Green Party candidate to replace outgoing mayor Stephanie Miner. One of his central campaign points was to restore the [[Erie Canal]] through Downtown Syracuse to help aide in the revitalization of the neighborhood, with the belief that 'Cities that capitalize on their waterways tend to have more vibrant downtowns<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.syracuse.com/news/2017/10/5_novel_policies_howie_hawkins_thinks_will_fix_a_broken_syracuse.html|title=Let's bring back the Erie Canal: 5 policies Howie Hawkins proposes to fix Syracuse|date=2017-10-31|website=syracuse|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>'. Hawkins won 4.1% of the vote (excluding write-ins) and lost to independent Ben Walsh (54,4%, excluding write-ins),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.syracuse.com/politics/2017/11/election_2017_complete_results_for_onondaga_county.html|title=Election 2017: Results for Syracuse mayor, other Onondaga County races|date=2017-11-08|website=syracuse|language=en|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref> the first independent in the City's history.\n\nOn April 12, 2018, Hawkins announced his third run for [[2018 New York gubernatorial election|Governor of New York]] on the Green Party line. Hawkins and running mate Jia Lee received 95,716 votes (1.7%).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nyenr.elections.ny.gov/ |title=NYS Board of Elections Unofficial Election Night Results |access-date=November 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120174014/https://nyenr.elections.ny.gov/ |archive-date=November 20, 2018 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==2020 presidential campaign==\n{{Main|Howie Hawkins 2020 presidential campaign}}\n\nThe 2020 presidential campaign of Howie Hawkins was informally launched on April 3, 2019 when Hawkins announced the formation of an [[exploratory committee]]. He formally announced his campaign on May 28, 2019, to seek the Green Party nomination for the presidency of the United States in the 2020 presidential election and later the [[Socialist Party USA]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Howie Hawkins, Syracuse resident, exploring run for Green Party presidential nod|url=https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/howie-hawkins-syracuse-resident-exploring-run-for-green-party-presidential/article_1bc6e864-e446-566c-a36e-690150d2422c.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403203904/https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/howie-hawkins-syracuse-resident-exploring-run-for-green-party-presidential/article_1bc6e864-e446-566c-a36e-690150d2422c.html|archivedate=2019-04-03|access-date=2019-04-03|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Howie Hawkins, Syracuse resident, exploring run for Green Party presidential nod|url=https://www.timesunion.com/news/article/Howie-Hawkins-will-seek-Green-nomination-for-13900737.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529005905/https://www.timesunion.com/news/article/Howie-Hawkins-will-seek-Green-nomination-for-13900737.php|archivedate=2019-05-29|access-date=2019-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn October 26, 2019, Hawkins won the nomination of the Socialist Party USA in his effort to unite smaller left-wing parties together.<ref>{{cite web|title=Howie Hawkins wins Socialist Party USA nomination for 2020 presidential race|url=https://www.localsyr.com/news/your-local-election-hq/howie-hawkins-wins-socialist-party-usa-nomination-for-2020-presidential-race/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191104051752/https://www.localsyr.com/news/your-local-election-hq/howie-hawkins-wins-socialist-party-usa-nomination-for-2020-presidential-race/|archivedate=2019-11-04|access-date=2019-10-28|url-status=live}}</ref> In November, Hawkins won the nomination of [[Solidarity (United States)|Solidarity]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Howie Hawkins for President |url=https://solidarity-us.org/atc/203/hawins-for-president/ |website=Solidarity |language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Background====\nIn the 1980s Hawkins joined the [[Green politics|green movement]] and in the early 1990s a press conference was held in Washington, D.C., that featured Charles Betz, Joni Whitmore, Hilda Mason, and Howie Hawkins to announce the formation of the [[Greens/Green Party USA]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Official Formation of the Green Party-USA|url=https://www.c-span.org/video/?20897-1/official-formation-green-partyusa|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019080559/https://www.c-span.org/video/?20897-1%2Fofficial-formation-green-partyusa|archivedate=October 19, 2016|url-status=live|access-date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> Later in December 1999, [[Mike Feinstein]] and Hawkins wrote the Plan for a Single National Green Party which was the plan to organize the [[Association of State Green Parties|ASGP]] and [[Greens/Green Party USA|GPUSA]] into a single [[Green Party of the United States|Green Party]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Greens/Green Party USA|url=https://www.greenparty.org/gatheringminutes.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810052904/https://www.greenparty.org/gatheringminutes.php|archivedate=2017-08-10|url-status=live}}</ref> Over the next decade he would run in multiple New York [[2006 United States Senate election in New York|Senate]] and [[2008 United States House of Representatives elections in New York|House]] races.<ref>{{cite web|title=0-for-23: An Undeterred Green Party Candidate on His Long Losing Streak|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/19/nyregion/howie-hawkins-green-party-governor.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426213550/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/19/nyregion/howie-hawkins-green-party-governor.html|archivedate=2019-04-26|url-status=live}}</ref> In [[2010 New York gubernatorial election|2010]] he surpassed the 50,000 vote requirement to stay on the ballot in the gubernatorial election and [[2014 New York gubernatorial election|four years]] later he received enough to move the Green Party line to Row D as he had taken one-third more than the [[Working Families Party]] and twice as much as the [[Independence Party of New York|Independence Party]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Third party's profile rises|url=https://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Third-party-s-profile-rises-5921969.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118121710/https://www.timesunion.com/local/article/Third-party-s-profile-rises-5921969.php|archivedate=2018-11-18|url-status=live}}</ref> However, in [[2018 New York gubernatorial election|2018]] he lost 80,000 votes, but retained ballot access and was only lowered one row down to Row E.<ref>{{cite web|title=Howie Hawkins wins enough votes to keep Green Party status in NY|url=https://www.syracuse.com/politics/2018/11/green_party_howie_hawkins_new_york_governor_2018_election.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412024252/https://www.syracuse.com/politics/2018/11/green_party_howie_hawkins_new_york_governor_2018_election.html|archivedate=2019-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref> In [[2012 Green Party presidential primaries|2012]] Hawkins was approached over the possibility of running for the Green Party nomination, but declined due to his employment commitments at [[United Parcel Service|UPS]] forcing him to campaign for offices in New York at most and would interfere with a national campaign.<ref>{{cite web|title=Why is Syracuse's Howie Hawkins running for president? 'It's hard to say no'|url=https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/why-is-syracuse-s-howie-hawkins-running-for-president-it/article_56758623-4e45-5635-859a-859f3889612b.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190410034427/https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/why-is-syracuse-s-howie-hawkins-running-for-president-it/article_56758623-4e45-5635-859a-859f3889612b.html|archivedate=2019-04-10|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHowever, following Hawkins' retirement he was approached again to run by a draft movement with a public letter addressed to him that was signed by former Green vice presidential nominees [[Cheri Honkala]] and [[Ajamu Baraka]], former Green mayoral candidate and [[Ralph Nader|Nader's]] 2008 running mate [[Matt Gonzalez]], and other prominent Green Party members.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sign On: Greens And Allies Urge Howie Hawkins To Seek Presidential Nomination|url=https://independentpoliticalreport.com/2019/03/sign-on-greens-urge-howie-hawkins-to-seek-presidential-nomination/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402141451/https://independentpoliticalreport.com/2019/03/sign-on-greens-urge-howie-hawkins-to-seek-presidential-nomination/|archivedate=2019-04-02|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Campaign====\n{{Main|Howie Hawkins 2020 presidential campaign}}\n\nOn April 3, 2019, Hawkins announced that he was forming an [[exploratory committee]] to prepare for a potential candidacy for the Green Party [[2020 United States presidential election|2020]] [[2020 Green Party presidential primaries|presidential nomination]] and later Hawkins formally launched his campaign on May 28, 2019, in [[Brooklyn |Brooklyn, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://auburnpub.com/blogs/eye_on_ny/howie-hawkins-syracuse-resident-exploring-run-for-green-party-presidential/article_1bc6e864-e446-566c-a36e-690150d2422c.html|title=Howie Hawkins, Syracuse resident, exploring run for Green Party presidential nod|first=Robert Harding|last=robert.harding@lee.net|date=|website=Auburn Citizen|accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://howiehawkins.us/|title=Howie Hawkins for President Exploratory Committee - A Green Ecosocialist for President|author=|date=March 29, 2019|publisher=|accessdate=April 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesunion.com/news/article/Howie-Hawkins-will-seek-Green-nomination-for-13900737.php|title=Howie Hawkins will seek Green nomination for president|date=May 28, 2019|website=Times Union|access-date=June 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn August 23, 2019, the Hawkins campaign announced they had met the requisite [[Presidential election campaign fund checkoff|federal matching funds]] for [[California]] and [[New York State|New York]].<ref>{{cite tweet|last=Hawkins|first=Howie|user=HowieHawkins20|number=1164962792375349248|date=23 August 2019|title=Thank you, @cagreenparty|accessdate=26 August 2019}}</ref> The campaign must receive $5,000 from residents, with no more than $250 counted for each contribution, in at least 20 states to qualify for the funds. Only his campaign and Steve Bullock's applied for primary season matching funds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Montana Governor Steve Bullock Will Apply for Primary Season Matching Funds|url=https://ballot-access.org/2019/09/30/montana-governor-steve-bullock-will-apply-for-primary-season-matching-funds/|website=Ballot Access News|last1=Winger|first1=Richard|date=September 30, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191002132702/http://ballot-access.org/2019/09/30/montana-governor-steve-bullock-will-apply-for-primary-season-matching-funds/|archivedate=2019-10-02|access-date=2019-09-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHawkins received the nomination of the [[Socialist Party USA]] on October 26, 2019.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=SPofUSA|number=1188213871359778816|title=The Socialist Party is excited to announce Howie Hawkins as its presidential nominee for the 2020 election!|date=October 26, 2019|author=[[Socialist Party USA]]|accessdate=October 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Main|Electoral history of Howie Hawkins}}\n\n==Publications==\n* {{cite book |last1=Hawkins |first1=Howard |title=Independent Politics: The Green Party Strategy Debate |date=2006 |publisher=Haymarket Books |isbn=978-1-931859-30-1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rxqIAAAAMAAJ&q |language=en}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Howie |first1=Hawkins |title=The Case For An Independent Left Party: From The Bottom Up |date=2020}}\n* [https://newpol.org/authors/hawkins-howie/ Howie Hawkins] [[New Politics (magazine)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://howiehawkins.us/ Howie Hawkins 2020 Presidential Campaign Website]\n*[http://www.howiehawkins.org/ Howie Hawkins 2014 Campaign Website]\n*[http://d3n8a8pro7vhmx.cloudfront.net/syracusegreens/pages/326/attachments/original/1381936146/The_Once_and_Future_Solution___position_paper.pdf \"Restore State Revenue Sharing Funded by Progressive Taxation: The Once and Future Solution to the City's Fiscal Crisis\"], position paper, October 16, 2013\n*[http://www.ontheissues.org/Senate/Howie_Hawkins.htm Howie Hawkins On The Issues, (2006)]\n*[https://www.amazon.com/dp/1931859302/ Independent Politics: The Green Party Strategy Debate], by Howie Hawkins, Haymarket Books, 2006.\n{{United States presidential election, 2020}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box | before=none| title=[[Green Party (United States)|Green Party]] Candidate for [[New York State Comptroller]] | years= 1998 and 2002 | after=[[Julia Willebrand]]}}\n{{succession box|before=[[David McReynolds]] | title=[[Green Party (United States)|Green Party]] Candidate for [[List of United States Senators from New York|United States Senator from New York]]|years= 2006|after=Cecile Lawrence}}\n{{succession box | before=[[Malachy McCourt]]| title=[[Green Party (United States)|Green Party]] Candidate for [[New York State Governor]] | years= 2010, 2014, 2018 | after=most recent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hawkins, Howie}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2016 United States vice-presidential candidates]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2020 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Activists from Syracuse, New York]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013nuclear power activists]]\n[[Category:American democratic socialists]]\n[[Category:Citizens Party (United States) politicians]]\n[[Category:Dartmouth College alumni]]\n[[Category:Green Party of the United States politicians]]\n[[Category:Industrial Workers of the World members]]\n[[Category:Labor Party (United States, 1996) politicians]]\n[[Category:Trade unionists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Members of Solidarity (United States)]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Greens]]\n[[Category:Peace and Freedom Party politicians]]\n[[Category:People from San Mateo, California]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Syracuse, New York]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 United States elections]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n", "name_user": "Landingdude13", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howie_Hawkins"}
